# Plotting distributions of some key features split by Fraud/Non-Fraud
features = ['amount', 'oldbalanceOrg', 'newbalanceOrig', 'oldbalanceDest', 'newbalanceDest']

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
for i, feature in enumerate(features, 1):
    plt.subplot(3, 2, i)
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, hue='isFraud', kde=True, element='step', bins=50)
    plt.title(f'{feature} Distribution by Fraud/Non-Fraud')
    plt.xlabel(feature)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In [6]:
# Create bins for the transaction amounts to group by ranges
data['amount_bin'] = pd.cut(data['amount'], bins=[0, 1000, 10000, 100000, 1000000, np.inf], labels=['<1k', '1k-10k', '10k-100k', '100k-1M', '>1M'])

# Plot a heatmap of fraud distribution by transaction type and amount bins
fraud_heatmap_data = pd.crosstab(data['amount_bin'], data['type'], values=data['isFraud'], aggfunc='sum')

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(fraud_heatmap_data, annot=True, fmt='.0f', cmap='YlGnBu')
plt.title('Fraud Count by Transaction Type and Amount Range')
plt.xlabel('Transaction Type')
plt.ylabel('Transaction Amount Range')
plt.show()

# We can potentially look at creating new features like
# balance_change_orig = oldbalanceOrg - newbalanceOrig and
# balance_change_dest = oldbalanceDest - newbalanceDest.

# These represent the change in balance for both the sender and receiver
# accounts as a result of the transaction

# Creating new balance change features
data['balance_change_orig'] = data['oldbalanceOrg'] - data['newbalanceOrig']
data['balance_change_dest'] = data['oldbalanceDest'] - data['newbalanceDest']

# Checking the first few rows with the new features
data[['balance_change_orig', 'balance_change_dest']].head()
